07879nam a22008775i 9780801470349DE-B159720210824034702.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||210824t20142014nyu    fo  d z      eng d  a97808014703497 a10.7591/97808014703492doi  a(DE-B1597)496472  a(OCoLC)877868631  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anyucUS-NY 7aPOL0190002bisacsh04a361.722304aThe Politics of Non-state Social Welfare /ced. by Lauren M. MacLean, Melani Cammett. 1aIthaca, NY : bCornell University Press, c[2014] 4c©2014  a1 online resource (328 p.) :b23 tables, 6 charts  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- tIntroduction -- t1. Mapping Social Welfare Regimes beyond the OECD -- t2. The Political Consequences of Non-state Social Welfare: An Analytical Framework -- tPart I States, Non-state Social Welfare, and Citizens in the Developing World -- t3. Empowering Local Communities and Enervating the State? Foreign Oil Companies as Public Goods Providers in Azerbaijan and Kazakhstan -- t4. The Politics of “Contracting Out” to the Private Sector: Water and Sanitation in Argentina -- t5. Blurring the Boundaries: NGOs, the State, and Service Provision in Kenya -- t6. Bridging the Local and the Global: Faith-Based Organizations as Non-state Providers in Tanzania -- t7. Sectarian Politics and Social Welfare: Non-state Provision in Lebanon -- t8. The Reciprocity of Family, Friends, and Neighbors in Rural Ghana and Côte d’Ivoire -- t9. The Naya Netas : Informal Mediators of Government Services in Rural North India -- tPart II The Politics of Non-state Social Welfare in Emerging Markets and the Industrialized World -- t10. Private Provision with Public Funding: The Challenges of Regulating Quasi Markets in Chilean Education -- t11. “Spontaneous Privatization” and Its Political Consequences in Russia’s Postcommunist Health Sector -- t12. State Dollars, Non-state Provision: Local Nonprofi t Welfare Provision in the United States -- tConclusion -- tReferences -- tContributors -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aAcross the world, welfare states are under challenge (or were never developed extensively in the first place) while non-state actors increasingly provide public goods and basic welfare. In many parts of the Middle East and South Asia, sectarian organizations and political parties supply basic services to ordinary people more extensively and effectively than governments. In sub-Saharan Africa, families struggle to pay hospital fees, and nongovernmental organizations (NGOs) launch welfare programs as states cut subsidies and social programs. Likewise, in parts of Latin America, international and domestic NGOs and, increasingly, private firms are key suppliers of social welfare in both urban and rural communities. Even in the United States, where the welfare state is far more developed, secular NGOs and faith-based organizations are critical components of social safety nets. Despite official entitlements to public welfare, citizens in Russia face increasing out-of-pocket expenses as they are effectively compelled to seek social services through the private market.In The Politics of Non-state Social Welfare, a multidisciplinary group of contributors use survey data analysis, spatial analysis, in-depth interviews, and ethnographic and archival research to explore the fundamental transformation of the relationship between states and citizens. The book highlights the political consequences of the non-state provision of social welfare, including the ramifications for equitable and sustainable access to social services, accountability for citizens, and state capacity. The authors do not assume that non-state providers will surpass the performance of weak, inefficient, or sometimes corrupt states but instead offer a systematic analysis of a wide spectrum of non-state actors in a variety of contexts around the world, including sectarian political parties, faith-based organizations, community-based organizations, family networks, informal brokers, and private firms.Contributors: Scott Allard, University of Chicago; Jennifer N. Brass, Indiana University; Melani Cammett, Brown University; Linda Cook, Brown University; Ian Gough, London School of Economics; Michael Jennings, School of Oriental and African Studies; Anirudh Krishna, Duke University; Pauline Jones Luong, University of Michigan; Lauren M. MacLean, Indiana University; Alejandra Mizala, University of Chile; Alison Post, University of California, Berkeley; Ben Ross Schneider, Massachusetts Institute of Technology.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Aug 2021) 0aCharitiesxPolitical aspects. 0aHuman servicesxPolitical aspects. 0aNon-governmental organizationsxPolitical aspects. 0aPublic welfarexPolitical aspects. 4aPolitical Science & Political History. 4aSociology & Social Science. 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / Public Policy / Social Services & Welfare.2bisacsh1 aAllard, Scott W., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBrass, Jennifer N., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCammett, Melani, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCammett, Melani, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aCook, Linda J., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGough, Ian, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aJennings, Michael, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKrishna, Anirudh, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLuong, Pauline Jones, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMacLean, Lauren M., ec